WEBVTT

00:01.349 --> 00:02.698
- Previously
on "God Friended Me"...

00:02.741 --> 00:04.047
- I'm running
the God Account code through

00:04.091 --> 00:06.745
the IdentitySeal server.

00:06.789 --> 00:08.573
- What the hell happened?
Dude, does this have something

00:08.617 --> 00:10.358
to do with the
software you were running?

00:10.401 --> 00:12.316
- No.
Maybe.

00:12.360 --> 00:14.405
- Can I have everybody's
attention?

00:14.449 --> 00:16.494
IdentitySeal has been sold.

00:16.538 --> 00:18.496
- To who?
- Simon Hayes.

00:18.540 --> 00:22.152
- Simon Hayes? He's like
the Bill Gates of A.I., dude.

00:22.196 --> 00:24.676
What if Simon Hayes is behind
the God Account?

00:24.720 --> 00:26.548
- When your mother
was in the audience,

00:26.591 --> 00:28.898
I played every note for her.

00:28.941 --> 00:31.292
- It may be time for you
to play for someone else.

00:31.335 --> 00:32.945
If you want it to be for Trish,

00:32.989 --> 00:34.773
that's okay-- Mom would want you to.

00:34.817 --> 00:36.906
- You're DJ Trek?
- I also go by Nia.

00:36.949 --> 00:38.342
- Miles.

00:38.386 --> 00:40.475
Cara and I are just friends.

00:40.518 --> 00:42.781
- I can't help but think that
there's more to that.

00:42.825 --> 00:44.218
- Everything okay?

00:44.261 --> 00:47.438
- Nia just
broke things off with me.

00:50.311 --> 00:54.532
[DENM's "Good Thing"]

00:54.576 --> 01:01.322
♪

01:18.643 --> 01:23.518
- My podcast is up 13%.

01:23.561 --> 01:25.563
Finally.

01:25.607 --> 01:27.913
♪

01:27.957 --> 01:30.742
"After a few episodes,
I can't stop listening."

01:30.786 --> 01:33.528
"Excited to know who's behind
the God Account."

01:33.571 --> 01:36.008
[knocking at door]

01:36.052 --> 01:37.923
- Surprise.

01:37.967 --> 01:39.925
- What's with the bags?
Is everything okay?

01:39.969 --> 01:41.666
- Yeah, everything's fine.

01:41.710 --> 01:43.277
Uh, found out last night

01:43.320 --> 01:45.235
my building's being
fumigated today.

01:45.279 --> 01:46.758
Is it cool if I crash here
for a couple days?

01:46.802 --> 01:49.413
- No, of course, of course,
as much as time as you need.

01:49.457 --> 01:50.762
Where's Dee?

01:50.806 --> 01:53.635
- She is at a dance workshop
in Chicago.

01:53.678 --> 01:56.899
So, lucky for you,
it's just me.

01:56.942 --> 01:58.640
- Okay, yeah, I...

01:58.683 --> 02:00.816
[chuckles]
I see what's going on here.

02:00.859 --> 02:02.905
- What?

02:02.948 --> 02:05.821
- Al, I'm fine, okay?

02:05.864 --> 02:07.257
Yes, I miss Nia,

02:07.301 --> 02:09.041
but this is not
my first breakup, okay?

02:09.085 --> 02:10.739
I don't need a shoulder
to cry on

02:10.782 --> 02:12.393
or a babysitter

02:12.436 --> 02:15.570
or my little sis taking time
to psychoanalyze me.

02:15.613 --> 02:18.486
- My building really
is being fumigated.

02:18.529 --> 02:20.444
- Really?
- [chuckles]

02:20.488 --> 02:22.446
Sorry to break it
to you, Miles,

02:22.490 --> 02:24.318
but not everything
is about you.

02:24.361 --> 02:25.971
- [chuckles]
- Oh, look at that.

02:26.015 --> 02:28.626
I did have the time
to psychoanalyze you.

02:28.670 --> 02:30.759
- Oh, okay, look,
I'll take the couch.

02:30.802 --> 02:32.761
The bedroom's all yours.
- Thank you.

02:32.804 --> 02:36.068
[gentle music]

02:37.635 --> 02:39.811
- This place feels different.

02:39.855 --> 02:42.292
We need to be on high alert.

02:42.336 --> 02:43.989
- For what exactly?

02:44.033 --> 02:45.817
- I don't know,
but you really think

02:45.861 --> 02:48.777
Simon Hayes buying IdentitySeal
is just a coincidence?

02:48.820 --> 02:50.996
- Bro, look, I admit the timing
is strange,

02:51.040 --> 02:52.911
but he's a tech billionaire.

02:52.955 --> 02:55.827
He probably buys tech companies
all the time.

02:55.871 --> 02:58.308
- Exactly.
It's like the perfect cover

02:58.352 --> 03:00.571
to spy on us,
see what we know.

03:02.834 --> 03:05.968
Uh...
Donald.

03:06.011 --> 03:09.798
Bro, that's my desk.

03:09.841 --> 03:11.626
- Not anymore.

03:11.669 --> 03:14.846
New management just reshuffled
desk assignments.

03:14.890 --> 03:16.500
- Oh, so everyone's
got new seats?

03:16.544 --> 03:19.068
- Actually, so far,
it's just you.

03:19.111 --> 03:21.026
Your new desk is now
over there.

03:21.070 --> 03:23.594
Also, they want to meet
with you tomorrow.

03:23.638 --> 03:24.987
- Why?

03:25.030 --> 03:26.510
- Don't know.

03:26.554 --> 03:29.339
I only ask questions
if it impacts me.

03:29.383 --> 03:32.516
[suspicious music]

03:32.560 --> 03:35.040
- What do you think management
wants to meet with you about?

03:35.084 --> 03:37.826
- No idea, but whatever it is,

03:37.869 --> 03:40.524
you can be sure
Simon Hayes is behind this.

03:40.568 --> 03:47.575
♪

03:53.494 --> 03:55.365
- Lord, we thank You for this,

03:55.409 --> 03:57.149
our blessed food,
for Your grace,

03:57.193 --> 04:00.718
as we are ever mindful
of the needs of others.

04:00.762 --> 04:01.719
Amen.

04:01.763 --> 04:03.765
- Bon appétit.

04:03.808 --> 04:06.550
- I'm sorry that I had
to cancel our last date.

04:06.594 --> 04:09.379
Um, a parishioner called.
They were in crisis.

04:09.423 --> 04:10.728
- You don't need to explain.

04:10.772 --> 04:12.774
I mean, I can't even imagine
what it's like

04:12.817 --> 04:14.993
having so many people
depending on you.

04:15.037 --> 04:16.908
- [laughs]
Well, thank you, but still,

04:16.952 --> 04:18.736
I know it can be frustrating.

04:18.780 --> 04:20.912
- I'm not gonna lie.
I...

04:20.956 --> 04:22.479
I would love
to see you more,

04:22.523 --> 04:24.742
but, look, life is busy--
I get it.

04:24.786 --> 04:26.440
I'm a mom of two.

04:26.483 --> 04:27.919
I'm the sole owner
of a music store.

04:27.963 --> 04:29.791
[both laughing]
I mean, I've had to cancel

04:29.834 --> 04:31.793
my share of plans myself,
trust me.

04:31.836 --> 04:34.448
- Yeah, you would think after
25 years, it would get easier.

04:34.491 --> 04:38.626
Well, maybe one of these days,
I'll take a break.

04:38.669 --> 04:40.628
- Hmm.

04:40.671 --> 04:42.456
You know...

04:42.499 --> 04:45.459
I have a farm upstate,

04:45.502 --> 04:47.852
and I haven't been in a while.

04:47.896 --> 04:49.811
Why don't we get away?

04:49.854 --> 04:52.466
- That sounds very nice.

04:52.509 --> 04:55.556
I can't even remember the last
time I've been out of the city.

04:55.599 --> 04:59.168
- Well, I think fresh air
might do you some good,

04:59.211 --> 05:02.476
and I can pick you up Sunday
after services.

05:02.519 --> 05:03.694
- Ah...

05:08.220 --> 05:12.181
[stammers]
It sounds wonderful...

05:12.224 --> 05:16.141
but Sundays are hard for me.

05:16.185 --> 05:19.884
Maybe...another time?

05:19.928 --> 05:23.061
- Sure. Sure.
Yeah, another time.

05:26.674 --> 05:28.980
- I'm telling you
something strange is going on.

05:29.024 --> 05:30.460
First, they want
to separate us,

05:30.504 --> 05:32.027
then they want
to meet with me.

05:32.070 --> 05:34.464
- If Simon Hayes really is
behind the God Account,

05:34.508 --> 05:35.944
why wouldn't he want to meet
with Miles?

05:35.987 --> 05:37.511
I mean, no offense,

05:37.554 --> 05:40.078
but he's the one
the God Account friended.

05:40.122 --> 05:43.473
- Speaking of Simon Hayes,
have you heard from Pria?

05:43.517 --> 05:45.519
- No, and how do you know
about her?

05:45.562 --> 05:47.999
- Because I listen
to your podcast.

05:48.043 --> 05:49.653
It's getting good.

05:49.697 --> 05:51.525
It's like "Serial," only
with people I actually know.

05:51.568 --> 05:53.701
- Hmm.
[both chuckle]

05:53.744 --> 05:55.180
- Maybe the new management
wants to meet with you

05:55.224 --> 05:56.834
because you're good
at what you do?

05:56.878 --> 05:59.010
- Doubtful. Last week
I put a customer on hold

05:59.054 --> 06:00.534
when I heard there was cake
in the break room.

06:00.577 --> 06:01.796
- [laughs]

06:01.839 --> 06:03.885
- Okay, not about customer
service.

06:03.928 --> 06:06.627
I mean, with computers.
You're a good coder.

06:06.670 --> 06:08.716
- Yeah, no, no, she's right,
and you also did apply

06:08.759 --> 06:10.195
for that I.T. job last year.

06:10.239 --> 06:12.110
Maybe it could be about that.
- You think?

06:12.154 --> 06:13.982
- I mean,
what seems more likely?

06:14.025 --> 06:16.811
Simon Hayes buys an entire
company just to spy on you,

06:16.854 --> 06:19.204
or someone at IdentitySeal
thinks your skills

06:19.248 --> 06:21.076
would be better off in another
area of the company?

06:21.119 --> 06:22.947
Occam's razor--
well played.

06:22.991 --> 06:24.558
[cell phone chimes]

06:24.601 --> 06:27.212
- Oh.

06:27.256 --> 06:30.868
Oh, got
a new Friend Suggestion.

06:30.912 --> 06:33.871
Felicia Washington.

06:33.915 --> 06:35.873
[cell phone chimes and buzzes]

06:35.917 --> 06:39.921
Wait, that's weird.
I just got another one.

06:39.964 --> 06:42.532
Jas--
[cell phone chimes and buzzes]

06:42.576 --> 06:44.273
- Another one?
- Yeah.

06:44.316 --> 06:46.971
[cell phone chiming
and buzzing]

06:47.015 --> 06:50.061
- Whoa.

06:50.105 --> 06:51.715
- Uh, bro,
is your phone broken?

06:51.759 --> 06:55.763
- No, I don't think so.
- How many are there?

06:55.806 --> 06:58.940
- We just got
76 Friend Suggestions.

06:59.984 --> 07:01.333
[cell phone chimes]

07:08.210 --> 07:10.430
- Jennifer Frost,
owner of a clothing store

07:10.473 --> 07:12.344
on Frederick Douglass
Boulevard.

07:12.388 --> 07:14.695
- Doris Ehrlich--
70 years old, retired.

07:14.738 --> 07:16.348
- Wait. Didn't we get
another Ehrlich?

07:16.392 --> 07:17.654
- Uh, yeah, yeah, Richard.

07:17.698 --> 07:19.308
- Oh, yeah,
it says they're married.

07:19.351 --> 07:20.962
Okay, so we have
one connection.

07:21.005 --> 07:23.399
- Great. So, if everyone
was at that wedding,

07:23.443 --> 07:25.488
maybe we're onto something.

07:25.532 --> 07:27.447
- Look, we all know how
the God Account works, okay?

07:27.490 --> 07:29.492
There must be something
that's connecting them all,

07:29.536 --> 07:32.147
maybe someone they all know.

07:33.409 --> 07:35.324
[inquisitive music]

07:35.367 --> 07:38.022
- Hey, wait, go back to
that last Friend Suggestion.

07:38.066 --> 07:40.895
Click on their profile pic.

07:42.897 --> 07:45.856
Yeah, look, that's the same
building that's in this photo.

07:45.900 --> 07:49.512
- Wait. Let me zoom in,
try and run an address search.

07:49.556 --> 07:50.948
- Morning.

07:50.992 --> 07:53.516
all: Morning.
- Any coffee left?

07:53.560 --> 07:55.387
- You know it's
10:00 a.m., right?

07:55.431 --> 07:57.607
- You know
I work nights, right?

07:57.651 --> 07:59.174
- I left the pot on.

07:59.217 --> 08:00.567
- Thank you.

08:00.610 --> 08:02.394
- No way.
- What?

08:02.438 --> 08:04.527
- I think I found a connection.
- What?

08:04.571 --> 08:07.182
- All 76 Friend Suggestions
have the same address--

08:07.225 --> 08:09.532
1204 East 123rd Street.

08:09.576 --> 08:11.447
- They all live
in the same building?

08:11.491 --> 08:13.231
- Okay, I'll call a Lyft.

08:13.275 --> 08:17.235
- Um, I have a meeting
with upper management today--

08:17.279 --> 08:19.542
some conference room
on the sixth floor.

08:19.586 --> 08:22.066
Unless--
Should I cancel?

08:22.110 --> 08:24.068
I mean, 76 Friend Suggestions
sounds like

08:24.112 --> 08:25.548
an all-hands-on-deck
kind of situation.

08:25.592 --> 08:27.245
- Oh, no, no,
go to your meeting.

08:27.289 --> 08:29.596
We'll be fine.
Call me when you're done, okay?

08:29.639 --> 08:31.423
- Good luck.
[door opens]

08:31.467 --> 08:34.470
- [sighs] Don't have
too much fun without me.

08:37.604 --> 08:39.649
- What'd I miss?

08:39.693 --> 08:41.651
- So how long is your sister
staying with you?

08:41.695 --> 08:43.610
- Oh, only for a few days.

08:43.653 --> 08:46.090
Just until her apartment
is done being fumigated.

08:46.134 --> 08:48.092
- Hmm, nice, a little
brother-sister bonding time.

08:48.136 --> 08:51.008
- [laughs] I'm pretty sure
she's just checking up on me,

08:51.052 --> 08:53.402
making sure I'm okay.

08:53.445 --> 08:56.579
- Are you?

08:56.623 --> 08:58.450
- Eh...

08:58.494 --> 09:00.017
- Well, having just been
through a breakup,

09:00.061 --> 09:03.238
I'm here if you want
to talk about it.

09:03.281 --> 09:04.935
- Thanks.

09:04.979 --> 09:06.981
And I think I'm good,
you know.

09:07.024 --> 09:10.071
When it's not right,
it's not right.

09:10.114 --> 09:13.117
- Yeah, I know what you mean.

09:13.161 --> 09:15.337
- On a positive note...
[both laugh]

09:15.380 --> 09:16.599
My podcast is up 13%.

09:16.643 --> 09:18.427
- That's great.
- Yeah.

09:18.470 --> 09:20.298
People are really digging
the God Account stories.

09:20.342 --> 09:22.126
I mean, half of the comments
are about Pria

09:22.170 --> 09:23.475
and whether or not
she's found Falken.

09:23.519 --> 09:24.607
- Yeah, well,
you have to admit

09:24.651 --> 09:27.610
it is a great mystery.

09:27.654 --> 09:30.570
So 76 Friend Suggestions.

09:30.613 --> 09:32.615
That is a lot of doors
to knock on.

09:32.659 --> 09:34.138
- Yeah, well, that's assuming

09:34.182 --> 09:36.488
we can even get
in the building.

09:38.708 --> 09:42.190
- Oh. Well, now that
we're both single,

09:42.233 --> 09:43.974
want to move in
together?

09:44.018 --> 09:45.497
- [laughs]

09:45.541 --> 09:48.500
That's a little fast,
but, okay.

09:48.544 --> 09:50.328
[both chuckle]

09:50.372 --> 09:51.634
- You guys are in luck.

09:51.678 --> 09:54.028
I just put the sign up
this morning.

09:54.071 --> 09:55.464
You'll be the first to see it,

09:55.507 --> 09:57.205
but if I were you,
I wouldn't wait too long.

09:57.248 --> 09:58.510
- Oh, yeah?

09:58.554 --> 10:00.338
- Yeah, not every day
an apartment

10:00.382 --> 10:02.079
opens up in this building.

10:02.123 --> 10:04.342
Most of the tenants here
are lifers, myself included.

10:04.386 --> 10:05.474
- Yeah, how long
you lived here?

10:05.517 --> 10:07.215
- Oh, since I was born.

10:07.258 --> 10:09.957
This place, I can't imagine
living anywhere else.

10:10.000 --> 10:12.960
It's more than just a building.
It's a true community.

10:13.003 --> 10:14.657
[elevator bell dings]

10:14.701 --> 10:18.095
- Oh, Mrs. Washington, hello.
How are you?

10:18.139 --> 10:20.315
- Doing just fine, William.

10:20.358 --> 10:22.230
- Well, that's good.
This is Miles and Cara.

10:22.273 --> 10:24.232
They're interested
in apartment 4D.

10:24.275 --> 10:25.668
- Oh, beautiful couple
like you?

10:25.712 --> 10:27.496
You all will fit right in.

10:27.539 --> 10:29.150
- Oh, that's so nice.
Did you hear that, sweetie?

10:29.193 --> 10:30.586
- Yes, I did.
- [chuckles]

10:30.630 --> 10:32.109
Did William tell you
he's a playwright?

10:32.153 --> 10:33.633
He's gonna be famous one day.

10:33.676 --> 10:36.244
- Oh, I don't know about that.
- Oh, nonsense.

10:36.287 --> 10:38.159
A famous writer lived here

10:38.202 --> 10:40.161
back when this place
was first built.

10:40.204 --> 10:42.380
William will carry on
that tradition.

10:42.424 --> 10:45.079
[laughing]
Well, nice to see you.

10:45.122 --> 10:47.124
- Okay.
Okay, take care.

10:47.168 --> 10:50.084
After you.

10:50.127 --> 10:51.520
[keys jingling]

10:51.563 --> 10:53.565
[indistinct chatter]

10:53.609 --> 10:57.004
- On your marks,
get set..

10:57.047 --> 10:59.049
- You're gonna want
to step aside.

10:59.093 --> 11:01.617
- [chuckles]
- Go!

11:01.661 --> 11:02.705
[children giggling]

11:02.749 --> 11:05.186
Oh-ho-ho!

11:05.229 --> 11:06.622
[children shouting happily]

11:06.666 --> 11:08.015
- Hey.

11:08.058 --> 11:09.712
Oh, that's Marcos, 4A,

11:09.756 --> 11:12.236
and his kids--
Mateo, Luca, and Nico.

11:12.280 --> 11:15.675
Here we are,
this is apartment 4D.

11:17.328 --> 11:18.765
The owner of the building

11:18.808 --> 11:21.681
renovated
the apartment recently.

11:21.724 --> 11:23.683
- Uh, are these new cabinets?

11:23.726 --> 11:28.122
- Uh, yep, updated appliances,
new fixtures, and new floors.

11:28.165 --> 11:30.080
- What about the water
pressure?

11:30.124 --> 11:32.082
[cell phone chimes and buzzes]
- Oh, it's the best.

11:32.126 --> 11:34.606
Uh, listen, I don't want
to rush you guys,

11:34.650 --> 11:36.130
but there's a tenant meeting

11:36.173 --> 11:38.785
about to start in
the common room.

11:38.828 --> 11:42.353
- Well, uh, you think it'd be
okay if we tag along?

11:42.397 --> 11:44.573
- Just to get a sense
of this amazing community.

11:44.616 --> 11:48.446
- Yes, of course,
it'd be my pleasure.

11:48.490 --> 11:52.276
- Mr. Singh.
Robyn Bell, HR.

11:52.320 --> 11:56.237
Let me start by asking, do you
like working at IdentitySeal?

11:56.280 --> 11:58.805
- Uh, yeah, very much.

11:58.848 --> 12:02.330
- And are you happy with your
position in customer service?

12:02.373 --> 12:03.679
- Absolutely.

12:03.723 --> 12:07.814
- You don't find it
uninspiring?

12:07.857 --> 12:11.556
- Okay. All right, I'm gonna
need you to level with me here?

12:11.600 --> 12:15.517
Is this about Simon Hayes?
Did he put you up to this?

12:15.560 --> 12:18.476
- I'm not sure I understand.
- I see.

12:18.520 --> 12:20.522
Are we done
with this little charade?

12:20.565 --> 12:22.393
'Cause I'd really like
to go back

12:22.437 --> 12:24.787
to my "incredibly uninspiring
life" in customer service.

12:24.831 --> 12:27.747
- So you're not interested
in a promotion?

12:30.358 --> 12:32.621
- Um...

12:32.664 --> 12:35.493
excuse me?

12:35.537 --> 12:38.845
- So, in addition to William
and Mrs. Washington,

12:38.888 --> 12:40.716
we have Marcos
and his three kids.

12:40.760 --> 12:42.849
- I found out
that his wife works.

12:42.892 --> 12:44.807
He's a stay-at-home dad.

12:44.851 --> 12:47.375
- Olivia teaches kindergarten,
moved back in with her parents

12:47.418 --> 12:49.333
until she can paid off
her student loans.

12:49.377 --> 12:52.249
- Yeah, and Shannon
and Karen Murphy--

12:52.293 --> 12:54.208
they're celebrating
their 20th next month.

12:54.251 --> 12:55.644
They invited
the entire building

12:55.687 --> 12:57.298
to a Guinness keg party
on the roof.

12:57.341 --> 12:59.343
- Reason enough to move in.
- [chuckles]

12:59.387 --> 13:01.650
- William was right--this is
a great group of people.

13:01.693 --> 13:04.218
Why would the God Account send
us their names?

13:04.261 --> 13:07.351
- Excuse me,
someone I got to talk to.

13:07.395 --> 13:10.137
Hi, what, uh--what are you
two doing here?

13:10.180 --> 13:12.313
- We need to speak
to our tenants.

13:12.356 --> 13:13.793
- About what?

13:13.836 --> 13:16.447
- I think it's better
if I address them directly.

13:16.491 --> 13:18.232
- Okay.

13:18.275 --> 13:21.583
- Hello, can I have
everyone's attention, please?

13:21.626 --> 13:23.846
If everyone can please
sit down.

13:23.890 --> 13:26.327
Thank you.

13:26.370 --> 13:27.850
Many of you know me.

13:27.894 --> 13:30.635
For those of you who don't,
my name is Denise.

13:30.679 --> 13:32.812
My father
and I own this building...

13:32.855 --> 13:34.770
or at least we did.

13:34.814 --> 13:38.687
Developers made us an offer
that we couldn't pass up.

13:38.730 --> 13:42.691
This building has been sold.
[crowd murmuring]

13:42.734 --> 13:45.563
Unfortunately,
the new owners...

13:45.607 --> 13:47.827
well, they plan to demolish
this property

13:47.870 --> 13:49.872
to build a luxury hotel.

13:49.916 --> 13:51.526
[crowd shouting]

13:51.569 --> 13:54.442
I'm sorry to tell you this,
but you have 30 days to vacate.

13:54.485 --> 13:57.445
[shouting continues]

13:57.488 --> 14:00.274
[somber music]

14:00.317 --> 14:02.145
- [sighs] Looks like we just
found out why

14:02.189 --> 14:04.974
the God Account sent
us their names.

14:11.328 --> 14:12.677
[crowd shouting]

14:12.721 --> 14:14.288
- Hector, I have lived here
all my life.

14:14.331 --> 14:17.160
You know that!
Where am I supposed to go?

14:17.204 --> 14:19.293
- Mrs. Washington,
I understand this is a shock.

14:19.336 --> 14:21.121
- A shock?
My parents can't move.

14:21.164 --> 14:22.513
What are they supposed to do?

14:22.557 --> 14:24.298
- We know you all have
a lot of questions,

14:24.341 --> 14:25.821
and we'll do our best
to answer them.

14:25.865 --> 14:27.779
- Denise, let's go.

14:27.823 --> 14:29.477
[shouting continues]

14:29.520 --> 14:31.348
- You know what this place
means to these people.

14:31.392 --> 14:33.220
You grew up here.
You can't do this!

14:33.263 --> 14:35.135
- Look, I know you've always
had a hard time

14:35.178 --> 14:37.833
understanding this,
but this isn't about me.

14:37.877 --> 14:40.314
It's just business.
That's all.

14:40.357 --> 14:44.840
- No, see, that's him talking.
That's not you.

14:44.884 --> 14:46.363
- Good-bye, William.

14:46.407 --> 14:48.888
[somber music]

14:48.931 --> 14:50.411
♪

14:50.454 --> 14:52.892
- Hey, is there anything
we can do to help?

14:52.935 --> 14:54.676
- I don't see how.

14:54.719 --> 14:56.330
I can't believe that
they would do this.

14:56.373 --> 14:59.202
I mean, I can see Hector,
but not Denise.

14:59.246 --> 15:01.161
- You seem to know her well.

15:01.204 --> 15:03.380
- I should.
She's my sister.

15:03.424 --> 15:05.730
- So that means
Hector is...

15:05.774 --> 15:08.908
- My father, yes.
We don't really talk anymore.

15:08.951 --> 15:11.649
He wanted me to take over
the real-estate business,

15:11.693 --> 15:14.609
and then I decided to follow
my dream of becoming a writer.

15:14.652 --> 15:16.350
After that, well, other than
letting me stay here,

15:16.393 --> 15:17.699
he turned his back on me.

15:17.742 --> 15:19.831
- So why don't you just talk
to your sister?

15:19.875 --> 15:21.398
- I wish I could.
Denise and I--

15:21.442 --> 15:23.313
we haven't seen
each other in a year.

15:23.357 --> 15:24.967
We used to be thick as thieves
growing up.

15:25.011 --> 15:27.187
It was the only way to survive
life under my father.

15:27.230 --> 15:29.450
- I have a sister, too, okay?

15:29.493 --> 15:31.756
Whenever my father and I were
going through something,

15:31.800 --> 15:33.628
my sister was there
when I needed her.

15:33.671 --> 15:35.673
There's a special bond
that can never go away

15:35.717 --> 15:37.893
no matter how long it's been.

15:37.937 --> 15:40.287
- Maybe you can get her
to talk to your dad

15:40.330 --> 15:42.245
about selling the building,
change their minds?

15:42.289 --> 15:44.204
- I really wish
I could believe that,

15:44.247 --> 15:45.509
but you heard her.

15:45.553 --> 15:46.858
She sounds like him now.

15:46.902 --> 15:48.512
Now, if you'll excuse me,

15:48.556 --> 15:50.819
I have to calm a lot
of nervous people down.

15:52.821 --> 15:55.302
Look, if he's not gonna
talk to her, then we need to.

15:55.345 --> 15:57.521
- You think there's a way we
can get her to change her mind?

15:57.565 --> 15:59.349
- Maybe, or at the very least

15:59.393 --> 16:01.221
convince her that kicking
people out of their homes

16:01.264 --> 16:03.701
could make
for very bad press.

16:03.745 --> 16:07.836
- And bad press
can scare off the buyers.

16:07.879 --> 16:11.405
- Hello, Mr. Singh.
I'm Dayna Chessin--

16:11.448 --> 16:13.450
the new VP of Technology
at IdentitySeal.

16:13.494 --> 16:16.236
- Is there
an old VP of Technology?

16:16.279 --> 16:17.977
- Not that I'm aware of.

16:21.067 --> 16:23.417
- Uh, so,
about that promotion

16:23.460 --> 16:25.549
the nice lady from HR
was telling me about...

16:25.593 --> 16:27.682
- We'll get to that.

16:27.725 --> 16:30.250
First, there's been
some suspicious incidents

16:30.293 --> 16:31.468
over the last few months

16:31.512 --> 16:33.340
that I wanted to talk
to you about.

16:33.383 --> 16:37.300
- Oh, uh, suspicious?
Like what?

16:37.344 --> 16:40.303
- For example,
on October 24th,

16:40.347 --> 16:43.393
someone tethered
the IdentitySeal mainframe.

16:43.437 --> 16:45.613
Do you know how to tether
a mainframe?

16:45.656 --> 16:48.920
- Me? No.
[chuckles nervously]

16:48.964 --> 16:52.620
I mean, I might--
I might.

16:52.663 --> 16:57.494
I do. I do,
but I didn't tether it...

16:57.538 --> 17:01.846
if that's what
you're asking me.

17:01.890 --> 17:04.066
[scoffs]

17:04.110 --> 17:06.547
- Can you tell me
about the Spiral Galaxy

17:06.590 --> 17:08.505
that appeared
on everyone's monitors

17:08.549 --> 17:10.464
after an unexplainable
system-wide meltdown?

17:10.507 --> 17:11.900
- I had nothing
to do with that.

17:11.943 --> 17:14.294
- So you're not aware
of a third-party code

17:14.337 --> 17:17.036
being analyzed at the time
that overloaded the system?

17:17.079 --> 17:19.342
- I'm gonna go with a no.

17:19.386 --> 17:21.475
- How about a breach
of the IdentitySeal mainframe

17:21.518 --> 17:22.867
a few weeks ago?

17:22.911 --> 17:24.086
Someone running

17:24.130 --> 17:25.870
a state-of-the-art
decryption program

17:25.914 --> 17:27.785
to break through firewalls.

17:27.829 --> 17:30.875
Let me guess, you had nothing
to do with that either.

17:30.919 --> 17:32.442
- [stammers, chuckles]

17:32.486 --> 17:35.010
You know, I'm so happy
in customer service,

17:35.054 --> 17:36.707
and if it's okay,

17:36.751 --> 17:39.841
I'd really like to pass
on this promotion.

17:42.017 --> 17:45.455
- I think I have everything
I need.

17:45.499 --> 17:47.022
That's all for today.

17:47.066 --> 17:50.939
[dramatic music]

17:50.982 --> 17:57.337
♪

17:57.380 --> 17:58.947
- Thanks for meeting with us.

17:58.990 --> 18:00.905
Like I said on the phone,
what's happening

18:00.949 --> 18:03.386
at your building might make
for an interesting op-ed piece.

18:03.430 --> 18:05.127
- Big bag wolf,

18:05.171 --> 18:07.651
huffing and puffing and blowing
people out of their homes.

18:07.695 --> 18:08.870
Is that it?

18:08.913 --> 18:11.351
- Isn't it?

18:11.394 --> 18:14.136
- No, it's not.

18:14.180 --> 18:16.878
How well do you know
my brother?

18:16.921 --> 18:19.533
- Actually,
we're new friends. Why?

18:19.576 --> 18:22.057
- As much as he thinks that my
father and I are the bad guys,

18:22.101 --> 18:24.103
no one wants to put anyone out
on the streets.

18:24.146 --> 18:26.061
We can help them relocate.

18:26.105 --> 18:28.542
That's what I went down there
for and was trying to explain.

18:28.585 --> 18:30.718
- Well, it's kind of hard
to hear anything after,

18:30.761 --> 18:33.024
"You have 30 days
to leave your home."

18:33.068 --> 18:34.765
- I get it,

18:34.809 --> 18:36.898
but that doesn't change
the facts.

18:36.941 --> 18:38.856
- If this really
is just about business,

18:38.900 --> 18:42.077
then there has to be a third
option that lets them stay.

18:42.121 --> 18:43.644
What about finding
another buyer?

18:43.687 --> 18:45.428
- If you have another buyer

18:45.472 --> 18:47.082
that doesn't want to tear
it down and build a high-rise,

18:47.126 --> 18:49.432
great,
but I'm guessing you don't.

18:49.476 --> 18:52.174
- What about the people
who live there?

18:52.218 --> 18:54.742
The tenants in the building
across from mine

18:54.785 --> 18:56.570
recently went co-op.

18:56.613 --> 18:58.485
Maybe they can do the same.

18:58.528 --> 19:01.401
- Organizing a co-op purchase
is a massive undertaking,

19:01.444 --> 19:03.577
and we have ticking clock
on closing this deal.

19:03.620 --> 19:05.448
- Well, then we'll work fast.

19:05.492 --> 19:08.756
♪

19:08.799 --> 19:10.714
- If you can get signatures
from all the tenants

19:10.758 --> 19:14.196
declaring their intent
to enter a co-op agreement,

19:14.240 --> 19:16.764
I can take the offer
to my father...

19:16.807 --> 19:19.158
see if I can convince him.

19:22.030 --> 19:24.598
- So how long are you staying
at your brother's?

19:24.641 --> 19:26.556
- Just a few days.
- Hmm.

19:26.600 --> 19:28.602
- Hey, how was lunch
with Trish?

19:28.645 --> 19:30.995
- Great. Uh, in fact...

19:31.039 --> 19:33.694
she invited me
to go to her farm upstate.

19:33.737 --> 19:35.913
- Wow, that's great.

19:35.957 --> 19:37.698
- But I said no.

19:37.741 --> 19:40.135
- How come?
Are things moving too fast?

19:40.179 --> 19:42.006
- What, for a trip upstate
to a farm?

19:42.050 --> 19:44.444
How old-fashioned
do you think I am?

19:44.487 --> 19:46.054
- Then what is it?

19:46.097 --> 19:49.492
- Well, she offered to come by after
Sunday service

19:49.536 --> 19:51.146
to pick me up.
- So?

19:51.190 --> 19:53.148
- So we've been seeing each
other for a few months now,

19:53.192 --> 19:56.195
and she's never asked
about coming to services.

19:58.197 --> 20:00.808
- Oh.

20:00.851 --> 20:02.940
Have you ever invited her?

20:02.984 --> 20:06.030
- Well, I...

20:06.074 --> 20:07.771
No.

20:07.815 --> 20:10.948
To be honest, I've just been
enjoying our time together,

20:10.992 --> 20:15.475
which probably
I should continue doing.

20:15.518 --> 20:17.520
- If that were true,

20:17.564 --> 20:21.045
I don't think we'd be having
this conversation right now.

20:21.089 --> 20:23.744
You always say,
if something's on your mind...

20:23.787 --> 20:27.182
- Best to get it out.

20:27.226 --> 20:29.228
Mm-hmm.
[chuckles]

20:31.839 --> 20:34.711
- Denise agreed to this.
- She gave us her word.

20:34.755 --> 20:37.279
Now, you'll still have to apply
for a loan at some point,

20:37.323 --> 20:38.976
but if you can get every tenant

20:39.020 --> 20:41.892
to sign at least
this petition of intent,

20:41.936 --> 20:44.199
she'll present the option
to your father.

20:44.243 --> 20:47.071
- I can't believe she's
actually willing to help.

20:47.115 --> 20:48.638
If you don't mind me asking,

20:48.682 --> 20:50.988
why are you guys
so invested in this?

20:51.032 --> 20:54.253
You can't like the apartment
that much.

20:54.296 --> 20:56.516
- We just want to help,

20:56.559 --> 20:59.083
and we both know how
complicated families can be.

20:59.127 --> 21:00.520
- Yeah.

21:00.563 --> 21:02.261
- Maybe when this is all said
and done,

21:02.304 --> 21:05.046
you and your sister
can start talking again.

21:05.089 --> 21:07.744
- I hope so.

21:07.788 --> 21:11.052
- All right, let's get to work.
We don't have much time.

21:11.095 --> 21:13.881
You will not regret this,
Olivia.

21:13.924 --> 21:15.796
Oh, and by the way,

21:15.839 --> 21:18.625
whatever you are cooking
smells amazing.

21:18.668 --> 21:20.540
- What guarantees do I have?

21:20.583 --> 21:22.281
- Well, none,
but if you don't sign,

21:22.324 --> 21:23.847
you're gonna be thrown
out of your home,

21:23.891 --> 21:25.240
and your kids won't have
this awesome hallway

21:25.284 --> 21:26.676
to run down anymore.

21:26.720 --> 21:28.548
- Mm, that's a good point.

21:28.591 --> 21:30.941
- Hey, Maria, how are you?
Listen, do you have a moment?

21:30.985 --> 21:32.334
- Yeah.
- Great, thanks.

21:32.378 --> 21:34.293
Just need a signature.

21:34.336 --> 21:36.164
- ♪ 'Cause the world
that we live in is crazy ♪

21:36.207 --> 21:38.253
♪ And it's difficult
to trust, trust, trust ♪

21:38.297 --> 21:40.821
♪ I'm feeling alive

21:40.864 --> 21:42.039
- Thanks.

21:43.780 --> 21:46.827
- Great. Thank you.
Thank you so much.

21:46.870 --> 21:49.308
- ♪ Alive, alive, alive

21:49.351 --> 21:51.962
- Thank you truly.

21:52.006 --> 21:53.964
♪

21:54.008 --> 21:55.662
Hey.

21:55.705 --> 21:58.621
♪

21:58.665 --> 22:02.364
- Oh, I wish my Harold
was still alive to see this--

22:02.408 --> 22:04.148
the whole building
coming together.

22:04.192 --> 22:06.194
You two really came
into our lives

22:06.237 --> 22:08.022
when we needed it the most.

22:08.065 --> 22:09.328
♪

22:09.371 --> 22:11.155
Isn't life funny like that?

22:11.199 --> 22:13.680
- Yeah.
Yeah, it is.

22:13.723 --> 22:15.116
- ♪ I'm feeling alive

22:15.159 --> 22:16.378
- I can't believe it.

22:16.422 --> 22:18.206
We're really gonna save
the building.

22:18.249 --> 22:20.817
- Yeah.

22:20.861 --> 22:22.645
- Just one signature left.

22:22.689 --> 22:26.301
- ♪ Alive, alive, alive,
I'm feeling alive ♪

22:26.345 --> 22:29.304
♪ I'm feeling alive,
alive, alive ♪

22:29.348 --> 22:31.785
♪ I'm feeling alive

22:31.828 --> 22:35.005
♪ I'm feeling alive,
alive, alive ♪

22:35.049 --> 22:37.007
- Let's go see my sister.

22:37.051 --> 22:39.314
♪

22:39.358 --> 22:42.186
- They're all there.
Every one.

22:42.230 --> 22:44.145
- I can't believe you were able
to pull this off.

22:44.188 --> 22:45.364
- Well, it wouldn't have
been possible

22:45.407 --> 22:47.061
without your brother's help.

22:47.104 --> 22:48.845
- People come together when
they believe in something.

22:48.889 --> 22:50.325
- Look, there's something
I need to tell you, William.

22:50.369 --> 22:53.023
After Cara and Miles left,

22:53.067 --> 22:56.810
I spoke to Dad about
the building going co-op.

22:56.853 --> 22:58.942
- He said no.
Of course he did.

22:58.986 --> 23:00.814
- You told us
to get those signatures,

23:00.857 --> 23:02.381
that you would try and convince
your father.

23:02.424 --> 23:03.991
- We gave those people hope.

23:04.034 --> 23:05.819
- I wanted this to work out.
I really did.

23:05.862 --> 23:07.734
- You sent us
on a fool's errand

23:07.777 --> 23:09.344
so Dad could close
the deal quietly.

23:09.388 --> 23:12.216
And let me guess--
it's already done.

23:12.260 --> 23:15.437
- William--
- Save it.

23:15.481 --> 23:17.134
You know what?
You are just like him.

23:17.178 --> 23:18.875
You don't care about anyone
but yourself.

23:18.919 --> 23:21.661
- Me?
What about you?

23:21.704 --> 23:22.966
- I would never turn my back

23:23.010 --> 23:24.707
on the people
that we grew up with.

23:24.751 --> 23:26.317
The people that we call family.

23:26.361 --> 23:28.058
- I know.
You only turn your back

23:28.102 --> 23:29.756
on your actual family.

23:31.801 --> 23:33.194
There's nothing else I can do.

23:33.237 --> 23:34.891
I just signed the papers.

23:34.935 --> 23:37.111
The building's been sold.

23:44.727 --> 23:47.643
[contemplative music]

23:47.687 --> 23:49.645
- So, if the building's been sold,

23:49.689 --> 23:51.865
how are you supposed to help
your 76 Friend Suggestions?

23:51.908 --> 23:52.996
- No idea.

23:53.040 --> 23:54.389
- Well, I highly doubt

23:54.433 --> 23:56.217
the God Account
sent you all their names

23:56.260 --> 23:58.175
just to have you rent
76 U-Hauls

23:58.219 --> 24:00.134
and bubble-wrap their stuff.

24:00.177 --> 24:01.831
- Well, I mean, you heard
Denise, saw how damaged

24:01.875 --> 24:03.746
her relationship
is with William.

24:03.790 --> 24:05.269
This must have something
to do with repairing it.

24:05.313 --> 24:07.010
- Yeah, well, that's great,

24:07.054 --> 24:09.752
but how is that gonna help
anyone living in that building?

24:09.796 --> 24:12.712
[cell phone chimes and buzzes]

24:12.755 --> 24:15.845
- It's Dee.
I'll call her back.

24:15.889 --> 24:17.238
Wait.
So what are you gonna do?

24:17.281 --> 24:19.849
I mean, it seems like you guys
are at a dead end.

24:19.893 --> 24:23.766
- Yeah, we tend to make things
worse before they get better.

24:23.810 --> 24:25.072
- [laughs]

24:25.115 --> 24:26.900
[cell phone chimes and buzzes]
Oh.

24:26.943 --> 24:28.858
The God Account--

24:28.902 --> 24:32.383
it just liked something called
The Little Red Lighthouse.

24:32.427 --> 24:34.211
- What's the
Little Red Lighthouse?

24:34.255 --> 24:37.171
- Wha--
it's in Fort Washington Park.

24:37.214 --> 24:38.868
Seriously?

24:38.912 --> 24:40.435
Guys, it's like
the first place I visited

24:40.479 --> 24:42.089
when I moved to New York.

24:42.132 --> 24:43.786
- The first place you visited
when you moved

24:43.830 --> 24:45.484
to one of the cultural
epicenters of the world

24:45.527 --> 24:47.398
was a tiny lighthouse?

24:47.442 --> 24:49.226
- [scoffs]

24:49.270 --> 24:51.272
- How tiny we talking
about, though?

24:51.315 --> 24:54.014
- Look, this must have to do
with our Friend Suggestion.

24:54.057 --> 24:56.103
- No, I agree, but what does
a little red lighthouse

24:56.146 --> 24:58.279
have to do with helping
76 people

24:58.322 --> 25:00.368
who are getting kicked
out of their homes?

25:00.411 --> 25:02.805
- I don't know,
but let's find out.

25:02.849 --> 25:05.416
- All right, you want to go?
- Uh, I can't.

25:05.460 --> 25:07.201
I got to go back
to IdentitySeal

25:07.244 --> 25:09.072
for one last meeting.
- For what?

25:09.116 --> 25:10.857
- Well, my guess is they're
gonna try and have me

25:10.900 --> 25:13.163
admit everything I've done
involving the God Account.

25:13.207 --> 25:15.992
It's never gonna happen.

25:16.036 --> 25:18.299
- Tagging along?
- I would love to.

25:18.342 --> 25:19.779
But I have to get to work.

25:19.822 --> 25:21.520
I'll hear about it
on the podcast.

25:21.563 --> 25:23.173
- Okay.

25:27.351 --> 25:31.094
[door opens, closes]

25:32.574 --> 25:34.881
- I'm glad you came down.

25:34.924 --> 25:36.970
I wanted to, uh, talk
to you about something.

25:37.013 --> 25:38.537
- Of course.

25:38.580 --> 25:40.539
Um, you know, but if this
about us going away together,

25:40.582 --> 25:42.758
I mean, there's really nothing
to talk about.

25:42.802 --> 25:45.282
If you feel like things
are moving too fast...

25:45.326 --> 25:47.284
- It's not that.

25:47.328 --> 25:49.112
I would love to see your farm,

25:49.156 --> 25:52.115
and I'm ready to take
the next step with us.

25:52.159 --> 25:55.510
- Me too.
[chuckles]

25:55.554 --> 25:58.774
I'm sensing a "but"
in there.

25:58.818 --> 26:03.474
- My church and the people
who fill the pews are my life--

26:03.518 --> 26:07.566
7 days a week,
365 days of the year.

26:07.609 --> 26:09.176
It's not a job.

26:09.219 --> 26:11.526
It's who I am.

26:12.875 --> 26:14.964
My life is blessed, and I want
to share that with you,

26:15.008 --> 26:16.487
but I need to ask,

26:16.531 --> 26:18.794
and I really want you
to think about it,

26:18.838 --> 26:21.362
is being a part of all of this

26:21.405 --> 26:23.973
something you'd even want?

26:24.017 --> 26:27.324
- You're saying that in order
for us to move forward,

26:27.368 --> 26:30.197
I need to become a part
of the church?

26:30.240 --> 26:33.504
- I can tell you it doesn't
matter whether you are or not,

26:33.548 --> 26:36.812
but my life and my faith are
one in the same.

26:36.856 --> 26:38.553
I don't know

26:38.597 --> 26:41.425
what our relationship
would even look like

26:41.469 --> 26:44.211
if you were not part of both.

26:44.254 --> 26:46.517
- I want to be,

26:46.561 --> 26:48.258
but I think you're right.

26:48.302 --> 26:50.260
I-I...

26:50.304 --> 26:53.046
I should think about this.

26:54.482 --> 26:56.353
- Nice to meet you, Rakesh.

26:56.397 --> 26:58.486
My name is Spencer Holt.

26:58.529 --> 27:00.140
- Using my first name,
building rapport,

27:00.183 --> 27:01.881
lower my defenses--
I get it.

27:01.924 --> 27:03.230
Okay, I saw "The Negotiator."

27:03.273 --> 27:05.449
I didn't want to see it,
but I saw it.

27:05.493 --> 27:08.409
- Terrible movie.
- The worst.

27:08.452 --> 27:09.932
Nice try.

27:09.976 --> 27:12.456
Okay, can we please
just get on with it?

27:12.500 --> 27:14.502
- Sure.

27:14.545 --> 27:17.940
You've denied any knowledge
regarding the activities

27:17.984 --> 27:19.594
my colleague discussed
with you yesterday.

27:19.638 --> 27:22.075
Is that correct?
- That's right.

27:23.511 --> 27:25.905
- Okay.

27:25.948 --> 27:28.864
Thanks for coming in.
[clears throat]

27:28.908 --> 27:31.432
- That's it?

27:31.475 --> 27:33.347
- Whoever's behind
all this has skills

27:33.390 --> 27:35.566
that are highly specialized.
- Meaning?

27:35.610 --> 27:37.177
- I seriously doubt whether

27:37.220 --> 27:39.135
you know what tethering
a mainframe even means,

27:39.179 --> 27:43.052
let alone how to do it
or why anyone would want to.

27:44.924 --> 27:48.057
- Maybe they were running
an AES-256-level

27:48.101 --> 27:49.885
decryption program
of their own design

27:49.929 --> 27:51.887
based on open ciphers
first approved

27:51.931 --> 27:54.585
by the NSA to protect
top-secret government files.

27:54.629 --> 27:57.980
Is that what you wanted
to hear, Mr. Holt?

27:58.024 --> 27:59.416
- Actually, yes.

27:59.460 --> 28:01.592
- Okay,
so, since I'm clearly fired,

28:01.636 --> 28:03.246
I'm just gonna show myself out.

28:03.290 --> 28:06.119
- You're not fired.

28:06.162 --> 28:07.686
Please.

28:09.688 --> 28:13.648
Your ability to find
and exploit weaknesses

28:13.692 --> 28:15.519
in their servers was the reason

28:15.563 --> 28:17.652
Mr. Hayes wanted me
to meet you.

28:17.696 --> 28:20.655
[breathes deeply]
I'm in charge of a new division

28:20.699 --> 28:22.613
we're starting
at IdentitySeal--

28:22.657 --> 28:24.964
Mobile Applications and Design.

28:25.007 --> 28:26.922
Simon wants to design
the first app

28:26.966 --> 28:29.098
that can not only monitor
someone's financial identity

28:29.142 --> 28:31.448
as it interacts
with global infrastructure,

28:31.492 --> 28:33.189
but something that can analyze

28:33.233 --> 28:35.931
and identify potential fraud
before it happens.

28:35.975 --> 28:37.541
- Predictive analytics.

28:37.585 --> 28:40.501
- I knew I had the right man.

28:40.544 --> 28:41.720
We see this application

28:41.763 --> 28:43.634
as the next cutting-edge
advancement

28:43.678 --> 28:45.375
in IdentitySeal's business.

28:45.419 --> 28:47.116
- You want me to work on it?

28:47.160 --> 28:48.552
- I want you lead the team

28:48.596 --> 28:52.295
that's going to code it
from the ground up.

28:52.339 --> 28:53.688
What do you say?

28:53.732 --> 28:56.343
- Uh...

28:56.386 --> 28:58.737
[laughs]

29:02.044 --> 29:05.700
- Wow. I did not know this was
in New York.

29:05.744 --> 29:09.051
- Hey, did you notice how Ali
acted when Dee called earlier?

29:09.095 --> 29:10.487
- Yeah.

29:10.531 --> 29:12.489
- Are you sure everything's
okay with her?

29:12.533 --> 29:14.448
Them?

29:14.491 --> 29:17.059
I mean, maybe this isn't about
her building being fumigated.

29:17.103 --> 29:19.322
- If there was something
going on, Ali would tell me.

29:19.366 --> 29:22.195
- Yeah, well,
not unless it was something

29:22.238 --> 29:24.197
she didn't want
to talk about.

29:24.240 --> 29:27.461
Look, she shouldn't have
to tell you.

29:27.504 --> 29:29.680
- Yeah, you're right.
- [chuckles]

29:29.724 --> 29:32.335
You gonna go check it out?
- Of course.

29:32.379 --> 29:35.338
[upbeat music]

29:35.382 --> 29:42.345
♪

29:42.389 --> 29:44.608
Wow.

29:44.652 --> 29:46.523
How'd you find this place?

29:46.567 --> 29:48.177
- My favorite book as a kid was

29:48.221 --> 29:51.006
"The Little Red Lighthouse
and The Great Gray Bridge."

29:51.050 --> 29:53.008
I used to read it
with my dad every night.

29:53.052 --> 29:55.010
It was about--
- A little red lighthouse?

29:55.054 --> 29:58.361
- [chuckles] Yeah.

29:58.405 --> 30:00.015
Yeah,
the lighthouse took pride

30:00.059 --> 30:01.582
in warning boats
of the shoreline,

30:01.625 --> 30:05.020
until one day men started
building a bridge above it.

30:05.064 --> 30:08.067
After they finished, the bridge
towered above the lighthouse,

30:08.110 --> 30:11.592
making it feel small
and powerless and unimportant.

30:11.635 --> 30:14.595
It was about the bridge
representing progress

30:14.638 --> 30:16.162
and the lighthouse fearing

30:16.205 --> 30:18.555
it would no longer be needed
or wanted.

30:18.599 --> 30:21.036
- Kind of like what's happening
at the Ruiz building.

30:21.080 --> 30:22.733
- Yeah, exactly.

30:22.777 --> 30:24.561
- [sighs]

30:24.605 --> 30:26.825
Well, maybe the God Account's
feeling thematic.

30:26.868 --> 30:28.565
How does it end?

30:28.609 --> 30:32.308
- Well, it realizes that it
can co-exist with the bridge

30:32.352 --> 30:34.789
and it's still useful.

30:34.833 --> 30:37.183
- Hmm.

30:37.226 --> 30:40.229
Yeah, let's look around,
see what we can find.

30:43.145 --> 30:45.452
Hey, check this out.

30:45.495 --> 30:47.584
"'The Little Red Lighthouse.'

30:47.628 --> 30:50.065
"This site was declared
a historic landmark

30:50.109 --> 30:53.373
"due to its connection
with Hildegarde H. Swift's

30:53.416 --> 30:55.462
famous book of the same name."

30:55.505 --> 30:56.855
Swift.

30:56.898 --> 30:58.465
- What?
What is it?

30:58.508 --> 31:01.424
- Remember Ms. Washington
said a famous author

31:01.468 --> 31:04.166
lived in the building
when it was first being built?

31:04.210 --> 31:06.777
- "The Little Red Lighthouse"--

31:06.821 --> 31:08.649
I think it was
published in 1942.

31:08.692 --> 31:10.346
- It's a pre-war building.

31:10.390 --> 31:12.174
- If she lived in the building
when she wrote the book,

31:12.218 --> 31:13.654
that could declare it
a historic landmark.

31:13.697 --> 31:15.438
- Which means the new owners
can't tear it down

31:15.482 --> 31:17.092
to build a high-rise.

31:17.136 --> 31:19.486
This is what the God Account
wanted us to see.

31:19.529 --> 31:22.750
This is how we can save those
people from getting evicted.

31:31.802 --> 31:33.717
- Mrs. Washington confirmed
the author's name

31:33.761 --> 31:34.980
who lived in the building
was Swift.

31:35.023 --> 31:36.503
- If she wrote a novel there,

31:36.546 --> 31:38.331
the building could be
a historical landmark.

31:38.374 --> 31:39.985
We just need proof.
- Is there any way to know

31:40.028 --> 31:41.900
what apartment she lived
in back then?

31:41.943 --> 31:43.771
Maybe we could find something
that showed she lived there?

31:43.814 --> 31:46.339
- She said it was 4D.

31:46.382 --> 31:47.775
- What?

31:47.818 --> 31:49.690
- That's why my father
renovated it so quickly.

31:49.733 --> 31:51.083
- He knew.

31:51.126 --> 31:52.998
- He must have figured
it out recently.

31:53.041 --> 31:56.001
It's why he pushed my sister
to sell the building so fast.

31:56.044 --> 31:57.741
- He was worried
if someone found out,

31:57.785 --> 31:59.134
he wouldn't be able to sell it.

31:59.178 --> 32:00.440
- But if he didn't disclose
something like that

32:00.483 --> 32:02.007
and someone found out,
he could end up in jail.

32:02.050 --> 32:03.660
Why risk that?

32:03.704 --> 32:05.967
Unless...

32:06.011 --> 32:10.276
My God.

32:10.319 --> 32:11.407
There's something
I need to tell you.

32:11.451 --> 32:12.931
- I don't have time for this.

32:12.974 --> 32:14.671
- It's about your father
and the sale of the building.

32:14.715 --> 32:17.283
- Denise, will you please just
listen to him?

32:17.326 --> 32:19.241
- You can't save
the building, William.

32:19.285 --> 32:20.503
- I'm not trying to save
the building.

32:20.547 --> 32:22.157
I'm trying to save you.

32:22.201 --> 32:24.464
- What are you talking about?

32:24.507 --> 32:26.509
- When we were kids,
do you remember

32:26.553 --> 32:28.163
how Mrs. Washington
would tell us these stories

32:28.207 --> 32:29.686
about how this famous author

32:29.730 --> 32:31.471
used to live in the building
when it was first built?

32:31.514 --> 32:33.777
- Maybe. Mrs. Washington
would tell us a lot of stories.

32:33.821 --> 32:36.519
- Yeah, well, that author's
name was Hildegarde H. Swift.

32:36.563 --> 32:38.739
- We think that Swift
wrote her book

32:38.782 --> 32:40.915
while living in apartment 4D.

32:40.959 --> 32:42.569
- Dad knew the building
could be declared

32:42.612 --> 32:43.874
a historical landmark

32:43.918 --> 32:45.528
and no one would be able
to tear it down.

32:45.572 --> 32:47.356
The new buyers wouldn't want
it anymore.

32:47.400 --> 32:49.184
That's why he had
the apartment renovated.

32:49.228 --> 32:51.578
- But that's fraud.
- Yes, it is.

32:51.621 --> 32:54.885
But lucky for him, his name
wasn't on the paperwork.

32:54.929 --> 32:56.887
- I-I can't believe
he would do that to me.

32:56.931 --> 32:58.715
- You said that I couldn't save
the building,

32:58.759 --> 33:00.717
and you're right,
but I believe you can.

33:00.761 --> 33:02.676
But you need to stand up
to him,

33:02.719 --> 33:04.765
and not for me and not for
the people in that building,

33:04.808 --> 33:07.550
but for you.

33:07.594 --> 33:08.987
- What if I can't?

33:10.989 --> 33:13.600
- I think you can.

33:20.433 --> 33:22.913
- We have a meeting.
Let's go.

33:22.957 --> 33:26.482
[somber music]

33:26.526 --> 33:28.310
Are you coming?

33:28.354 --> 33:31.313
- You go ahead.
I'll be right there.

33:31.357 --> 33:37.363
♪

33:39.017 --> 33:40.757
- I still haven't heard from my sister.

33:40.801 --> 33:43.369
I can't believe I have to break
the news to everyone again.

33:43.412 --> 33:46.415
- [sighs] I'm sorry. I wish
we could have been more help.

33:46.459 --> 33:47.677
- No, are you kidding me?

33:47.721 --> 33:49.462
You guys did everything
you could.

33:49.505 --> 33:52.508
I really appreciate it.
Thank you.

33:52.552 --> 33:55.294
- Well, it was
our pleasure, William.

33:59.037 --> 34:02.257
- Thank you so much for coming
on such short notice,

34:02.301 --> 34:06.261
but I wanted to deliver
this in person.

34:06.305 --> 34:07.784
It brings me great sadness

34:07.828 --> 34:12.441
to tell you that we couldn't
save the building.

34:12.485 --> 34:15.401
I'm sorry I let you all down.
[stammers]

34:15.444 --> 34:17.577
What are you doing here?

34:17.620 --> 34:20.449
- I have to speak
to my tenants.

34:20.493 --> 34:26.020
♪

34:26.064 --> 34:29.589
- The floor's yours.

34:29.632 --> 34:31.460
- Hello, everyone.

34:31.504 --> 34:35.464
It has come to my attention
that the buyers have received

34:35.508 --> 34:37.814
an anonymous tip
that this building

34:37.858 --> 34:39.990
might be a historical landmark.

34:40.034 --> 34:41.992
And since they can't
tear it down,

34:42.036 --> 34:45.735
they no longer see
the same value in the property.

34:45.779 --> 34:48.738
They've decided to walk away
from the deal.

34:48.782 --> 34:50.610
- So where does that leave us?

34:50.653 --> 34:52.655
- With a new buyer...

34:52.699 --> 34:55.310
one that my father just sold
to an hour ago.

34:55.354 --> 34:56.659
And I have it on good authority

34:56.703 --> 34:58.313
that the new owner
of the building

34:58.357 --> 35:00.707
has no intention
of evicting anyone.

35:00.750 --> 35:02.665
[crowd murmuring happily]

35:02.709 --> 35:04.885
- Wait, wait, how do you know?

35:06.626 --> 35:08.802
- Well,
because I'm the new owner,

35:08.845 --> 35:10.804
and no one
is going anywhere.

35:10.847 --> 35:13.850
[cheers and applause]

35:13.894 --> 35:16.853
[upbeat music]

35:16.897 --> 35:18.812
♪

35:18.855 --> 35:22.337
- Wait, so--
so you actually did it?

35:22.381 --> 35:24.426
You stood up to Dad.
- Thanks to you.

35:24.470 --> 35:26.341
- So what did he say?

35:26.385 --> 35:29.344
- He told me that when the old
tenants at 4D were moving out,

35:29.388 --> 35:31.825
they found an old photograph

35:31.868 --> 35:35.350
of a woman sitting
at a typewriter by the window.

35:35.394 --> 35:38.397
- Hildegarde H. Swift.

35:38.440 --> 35:41.835
- Dad destroyed the photo--
never one to take chances.

35:41.878 --> 35:44.533
He renovated the entire
apartment for good measure.

35:44.577 --> 35:46.013
- And he just told you
all this?

35:46.056 --> 35:47.710
- I was very persuasive,

35:47.754 --> 35:50.670
and as part of our agreement
and staying silent,

35:50.713 --> 35:53.803
he sold me the building
at a family rate.

35:53.847 --> 35:56.545
- [laughs]
[Cara laughs]

35:56.589 --> 35:57.894
You blackmailed Dad.

35:57.938 --> 36:00.636
[both laugh]

36:00.680 --> 36:03.073
- Well, to be honest,
I think he was proud.

36:03.117 --> 36:05.075
[laughter]

36:05.119 --> 36:06.599
- Okay.

36:06.642 --> 36:08.557
Well, now that the building
isn't being sold,

36:08.601 --> 36:12.126
are you guys still interested
in the apartment?

36:12.170 --> 36:13.823
- Oh.

36:15.608 --> 36:17.566
- The idea of family

36:17.610 --> 36:19.786
represents something different
to all of us.

36:19.829 --> 36:21.527
- Welcome.

36:21.570 --> 36:23.964
- For some,
it's the community of people

36:24.007 --> 36:27.924
who depend on you
for strength and guidance.

36:27.968 --> 36:29.535
- Good morning.

36:29.578 --> 36:32.799
- ♪ All of what I know

36:32.842 --> 36:34.801
♪

36:34.844 --> 36:37.934
- I am so happy you came.

36:37.978 --> 36:40.763
- So am I.

36:40.807 --> 36:43.810
I'm not sure what I'm getting
myself into

36:43.853 --> 36:48.162
or everything that
Reverend Finer's life entails,

36:48.206 --> 36:49.859
but I'm ready to find out.

36:49.903 --> 36:51.992
- ♪ I can only hear...

36:52.035 --> 36:54.603
[both laugh]

36:54.647 --> 36:57.215
- For others,
it's the unbreakable bond

36:57.258 --> 37:00.696
between a brother
and a sister.

37:00.740 --> 37:02.568
- I am proud of you, Miles.
- [chuckles]

37:02.611 --> 37:05.701
- 76 happily-ever-afters?

37:05.745 --> 37:07.225
You've outdone yourself.

37:07.268 --> 37:10.228
- So have you heard anything
about your apartment?

37:10.271 --> 37:12.665
- No, nothing yet.
Why?

37:12.708 --> 37:14.797
Are you trying to get rid
of me already?

37:14.841 --> 37:18.061
- No, no, no, no, it's just,
uh, Cara had mentioned

37:18.105 --> 37:19.976
when her apartment
was getting fumigated,

37:20.020 --> 37:22.501
they gave her
two weeks' notice,

37:22.544 --> 37:25.025
not a day.

37:25.068 --> 37:27.462
What's going on, sis?

37:27.506 --> 37:30.204
- Dee and I got
into a huge fight,

37:30.248 --> 37:33.599
and I just needed
some space--

37:33.642 --> 37:36.558
at least that's
what I thought.

37:36.602 --> 37:39.257
But having this time
to clear my head,

37:39.300 --> 37:42.172
really think about things...

37:42.216 --> 37:46.612
Dee is an amazing person,
but I...

37:46.655 --> 37:50.224
I just don't think
she's the right one for me.

37:50.268 --> 37:52.531
- Well, I'm sorry.

37:52.574 --> 37:55.011
- For what?

37:55.055 --> 37:57.971
- For not asking you.

37:58.014 --> 38:00.843
You have always been
there for me,

38:00.887 --> 38:04.543
always known what I was going
through and how to help.

38:04.586 --> 38:06.936
♪

38:06.980 --> 38:09.025
I'm lucky to have you.

38:09.069 --> 38:10.810
♪

38:10.853 --> 38:13.552
- I'm glad you feel that way,

38:13.595 --> 38:15.554
because you're
gonna be happy to have me

38:15.597 --> 38:16.772
a little while longer.

38:16.816 --> 38:19.122
[both chuckle]

38:19.166 --> 38:22.691
- And, yes,
sometimes those family bonds

38:22.735 --> 38:25.607
can get fractured
or even forgotten,

38:25.651 --> 38:29.568
but as long
as you never give up on them,

38:29.611 --> 38:31.961
you can always find
your way back.

38:32.005 --> 38:34.050
- It's just
a housewarming gift.

38:34.094 --> 38:35.748
- Thank you.
- [chuckles]

38:35.791 --> 38:38.054
- I know moving back here
is crazy,

38:38.098 --> 38:40.274
but this building
is the only place

38:40.318 --> 38:42.537
that's ever made me feel
like I'm at home,

38:42.581 --> 38:44.539
and I've missed that.

38:44.583 --> 38:46.759
I've missed you.

38:46.802 --> 38:48.282
[chuckles]

38:48.326 --> 38:52.025
- ♪ Find my peace,
love I feel ♪

38:52.068 --> 38:54.636
- Hey, how's Ali?
- She's holding up.

38:54.680 --> 38:56.072
- Thanks for coming by
to cheer her up.

38:56.116 --> 38:57.857
- Yeah.

38:57.900 --> 39:00.033
- And bringing more ice cream

39:00.076 --> 39:02.078
than anyone could ever
possibly eat in a night.

39:02.122 --> 39:04.037
- Trust me, that's the point.
[chuckles]

39:04.080 --> 39:05.908
- Oh.

39:05.952 --> 39:08.911
Got you a little something.
- What? [chuckles]

39:08.955 --> 39:11.261
"The Little Red Lighthouse
and the Great Gray Bridge."

39:11.305 --> 39:13.655
- First edition.

39:15.309 --> 39:17.920
Just a little God Account
case closed gift.

39:17.964 --> 39:20.314
- Wait.
We're doing that now?

39:20.358 --> 39:24.274
[chuckles] Thank you, Miles.
- No worries.

39:24.318 --> 39:26.755
I actually gave it a read.
It's not bad.

39:26.799 --> 39:28.801
- You know, you're like
the best fake boyfriend

39:28.844 --> 39:31.760
I've ever had.

39:31.804 --> 39:34.110
[chuckles]

39:34.154 --> 39:37.026
- I'm supposed to be gorging
myself on ice cream

39:37.070 --> 39:39.942
as you people tell me it's all
going to be okay.

39:39.986 --> 39:41.248
Or do we not remember the plan?

39:41.291 --> 39:44.120
- Oh, no, we remember.
[laughter]

39:44.164 --> 39:46.775
- Thank you.
- Uh-huh.

39:46.819 --> 39:51.171
♪

39:51.214 --> 39:53.173
[knocking at door]

39:53.216 --> 39:57.003
- ♪ All I see is
how I could change it all ♪

39:57.046 --> 39:59.048
- Oh, hey.
- Hi.

39:59.092 --> 40:01.747
- ♪ Find my peace,
love I feel ♪

40:01.790 --> 40:03.618
- What's up?

40:03.662 --> 40:08.014
- Rakesh Singh,
Head of Mobile App Design.

